Incorporated on February 18, 1907, the Town of Cathlamet is a municipality governed by six elected officials consisting of a mayor and five council members. Among the town's services are fire protection, emergency medical services, street maintenance, parks and recreation, a public swimming pool and library, general administrative services, and water and wastewater utilities. The town occupies a total area of .51 square miles in rural Wahkiakum County and has an estimated population of 520. Every third Saturday in July, Cathlamet celebrates Bald Eagle Days, an all-day event that closes Main Street for a parade and street fair. GOVERNMENT STRUCTURE. Governed by the Mayor/Council form of government and Title 35.27 RCW , Cathlamet has an elected mayor and five nonpartisan council members each serving a 4-year term. It was home to the Kathlamet people . In 1792, a British explorer named Lt. W.R. Broughton saw the village. Later, in 1805, famous explorers Lewis and Clark visited. They noted that about 300-400 people lived there in houses made of cedar wood. The first permanent non-Native settler was James Albion Birnie in 1846. He had worked for the Hudson's Bay Company , a big fur trading business. Birnie set up a trading post in the area. He first called the place "Birnie's Retreat." Incorporated on February 18, 1907, the Town of Cathlamet is a municipality governed by six elected officials consisting of a mayor and five council members. Among the town's services are fire protection, emergency medical services, street maintenance, parks and recreation, a public swimming pool and library, general administrative services, and water and wastewater utilities. The town occupies a total area of .51 square miles in rural Wahkiakum County and has an estimated population of 520. Every third Saturday in July, Cathlamet celebrates Bald Eagle Days, an all-day event that closes Main Street for a parade and street fair. GOVERNMENT STRUCTURE. Governed by the Mayor/Council form of government and Title 35.27 RCW , Cathlamet has an elected mayor and five nonpartisan council members each serving a 4-year term. It was home to the Kathlamet people . In 1792, a British explorer named Lt. W.R. Broughton saw the village. Later, in 1805, famous explorers Lewis and Clark visited. They noted that about 300-400 people lived there in houses made of cedar wood. The first permanent non-Native settler was James Albion Birnie in 1846. He had worked for the Hudson's Bay Company , a big fur trading business. Birnie set up a trading post in the area. He first called the place "Birnie's Retreat." messages.content:
Goal: Find the population difference between Washington’s largest and smallest county seats by land area, using 2020 Decennial Census populations from data.census.gov.

- Largest county seat by land area: Seattle (largest municipality by land area in Washington; Seattle is King County’s seat)
- Smallest county seat by land area: Cathlamet (Wahkiakum County seat; land area 0.51 sq mi)

2020 Decennial Census P1 populations on data.census.gov:
- Seattle city, Washington: 737015
- Cathlamet town, Washington: 560

Difference: 737015 − 560 = 736455

FINAL ANSWER: 736455
